******
[2]
Date: Wed 12 Dec 2007
Source: Express India.com [edited]
<http://www.expressindia.com/latest-news/Chambal-river-12-ghariyals-found-dead-in-last-two-days/249159/>


In the last 2 days, as many as 12 gharials have been found dead in
the Chambal River in Etawah's Chakar Nagar Tehsil.

While 4 carcasses were found on the banks, the other 8 were found
floating in the water. The deaths came under scrutiny after the NGO,
Society for Conservation of Nature, informed the Forest department
that it had spotted 2 dead crocodiles near the river. Department
officials visited the spot and took up the matter with the National
Chambal Sanctuary authorities.

Immediately after word was out, the Madhya Pradesh Forest department
also launched a search in the river. They found 4 carcasses in their
area.

District Magistrate of Etawah, Amit Gupta said, "We have sent the
carcasses for medical tests to find out the cause of death. The
Madhya Pradesh government is also carrying out similar tests."
Additional District Magistrate of Chakar Nagar Ali Hasan said while
the bodies were discovered in the last couple of days, the crocodiles
might have died earlier. He said a team of doctors and other wildlife
experts were trying to find out what could have killed crocodiles in
such large numbers.

Secretary of the NGO, Society for Conservation of Nature, Rajeev
Chauhan said, "I was informed by locals on Monday morning [10 Dec
2007] that 4 dead gharials had washed up on the river bank. I went to
check and found only 2 after which we informed forest authorities."

Senior officers of the Forest department have said that pollution in
the river waters was the likely cause behind the deaths. An officer
said it could also be a contagious disease. "The tests will reveal
the exact cause of death," he said. Despite several attempts,
officials of the National Chambal Sanctuary could not be contacted.

[Byline: Manish Sahu]

